  "local_port": 51772,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I prepare for GRE in 20 days?",
  "response": "Preparing for the GRE in just 20 days is challenging but doable with a focused and strategic approach. Here\u2019s a step-by-step plan to maximize your preparation:\n\n---\n\n### **Step 1: Understand the GRE Structure**\n- **Sections**: Analytical Writing (2 essays), Verbal Reasoning (2 sections), Quantitative Reasoning (2 sections), and an unscored research section.\n- **Scoring**: Verbal and Quant are scored on a scale of 130-170; Analytical Writing is scored on a 0-6 scale.\n- **Time Per Section**: \n  - Verbal: 30 minutes per section\n  - Quant: 35 minutes per section\n  - Analytical Writing: 60 minutes total\n\n---\n\n### **Step 2: Take a Diagnostic Test**\n1. Take a full-length GRE practice test (ETS PowerPrep or other reputable sources).\n2. Analyze your strengths and weaknesses in Verbal, Quant, and Analytical Writing.\n3. Set a target score based on your diagnostic test and the programs you\u2019re applying to.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 3: Create a Study Plan**\nBreak your 20 days into manageable chunks:\n\n#### **Days 1-5: Build Foundations**\n- **Verbal**: Focus on vocabulary (use GRE word lists like Magoosh or Manhattan Prep). Learn strategies for Text Completion, Sentence Equivalence, and Reading Comprehension.\n- **Quant**: Review basic math concepts (arithmetic, algebra, geometry, data analysis). Use resources like ETS GRE Math Review or Manhattan Prep.\n- **Analytical Writing**: Review the essay structure. Practice writing one Issue essay and one Argument essay.\n\n#### **Days 6-15: Practice and Refine**\n- **Verbal**: Practice 20-30 questions daily. Focus on reading comprehension and text completion strategies.\n- **Quant**: Solve 20-30 problems daily. Focus on weak areas. Memorize formulas and shortcuts.\n- **Analytical Writing**: Write 2-3 essays per week. Get feedback if possible.\n- **Full-Length Tests**: Take at least 2-3 practice tests (e.g., ETS PowerPrep, Manhattan Prep) to simulate test conditions.\n\n#### **Days 16-20: Final Prep and Review**\n- **Verbal**: Review vocabulary. Practice timed sections.\n- **Quant**: Focus on error analysis. Solve high-difficulty questions.\n- **Analytical Writing**: Practice timed essays.\n- **Full-Length Tests**: Take 1-2 more tests to build stamina and confidence.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 4: Use the Right Resources**\n- **Official GRE Materials**: ETS Official Guide, PowerPrep tests.\n- **Verbal**: Magoosh GRE Vocabulary Flashcards, Manhattan Prep GRE Verbal Strategy Guide.\n- **Quant**: Manhattan Prep GRE Math Strategy Guides.\n- **Analytical Writing**: ETS Analytical Writing Sample Essays.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 5: Focus on Time Management**\n- Practice answering questions under timed conditions.\n- Allocate time wisely during the test (e.g., 1.5 minutes per Verbal question, 2 minutes per Quant question).\n\n---\n\n### **Step 6: Stay Consistent and Manage Stress**\n- Study for 4-6 hours daily, but take breaks to avoid burnout.\n- Stay motivated by tracking your progress and celebrating small wins.\n- Get enough sleep, especially the night before the test.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 7: Test-Day Tips**\n- Arrive early at the test center with required identification.\n- Bring snacks and water for the breaks.\n- Stay calm and confident\u2014you\u2019ve prepared well!\n\n---\n\nBy following this plan and staying disciplined, you can make significant progress in 20 days. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
